        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Search Generative Experience (SGE)</strong> — now branded as AI Overviews in Google Search — is Google's integration of generative AI into search results. The system uses large language models to generate direct answers synthesized from multiple web sources, appearing at the top of the results page. Traditional search returns links; SGE returns generated answers with supporting source citations. For SEO, the strategic imperative has shifted from ranking first to being cited as a source.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR drop (AI Overview present)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">34–61% overall</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">AI &amp; Emerging</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR gain (if cited)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+35% vs non-cited</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">SGE represents the most significant structural change to Google search since the introduction of featured snippets. Understanding what it is, how it selects sources, and how to optimize for citation is now a core SEO competency.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Search Generative Experience (SGE)?</h2>
        <p>SGE is Google's AI-powered answer layer that appears above organic results for qualifying queries. When a user submits a query that Google determines would benefit from a synthesized answer, the system retrieves relevant pages from its index, extracts key information using a large language model, generates a direct answer, and displays it with links to source pages.</p>
        <p>The system was tested as "Search Generative Experience" in Google Search Labs from 2023. In 2024, Google rolled it out broadly under the name "AI Overviews." The underlying technology is the same; the brand name changed at launch.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The citation asymmetry</div>
          <p>When an AI Overview appears, overall organic CTR drops 34–61%. But sites cited within the AI Overview receive <strong>35% more clicks than non-cited sites</strong> ranking in the same positions. Being cited is not just a visibility win — it is a traffic advantage over competitors who rank nearby but are not included.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why SGE matters for SEO in 2026</h2>
        <p>SGE changes the fundamental metric of organic success. Ranking #1 for a query that triggers an AI Overview no longer guarantees the same traffic it once did — because the AI Overview answers the query before the user needs to click anything.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Position 1 CTR drops 30–40% when an AI Overview is present.</strong> A keyword that once delivered 2,000 monthly visits from a #1 ranking may now deliver 1,200–1,400 with an AI Overview in place.</li>
          <li><strong>Positions 4–10 lose 50–70% of their expected clicks.</strong> These positions, already low on the CTR curve, become nearly irrelevant when an AI Overview covers the query fully.</li>
          <li><strong>Citation is the new #1.</strong> A page cited in the AI Overview receives more clicks than a non-cited #2–#3 result. Citation is now a distinct optimization target separate from traditional ranking.</li>
          <li><strong>Content quality requirements are higher.</strong> AI systems evaluate factual accuracy, comprehensiveness, structure, and expertise signals when selecting sources. Surface-level content that ranked for keyword density no longer qualifies.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How SGE / AI Overviews works technically</h2>
        <p>The technical process has six steps:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Query analysis:</strong> Google determines whether a generated answer would benefit the user for this specific query type</li>
          <li><strong>Source retrieval:</strong> Relevant pages are retrieved from Google's existing index using standard ranking signals</li>
          <li><strong>Information extraction:</strong> The LLM extracts key claims, facts, and explanations from retrieved pages</li>
          <li><strong>Answer generation:</strong> The model synthesizes extracted information into a cohesive direct answer</li>
          <li><strong>Citation linking:</strong> Source pages are linked within and below the generated answer</li>
          <li><strong>Safety checking:</strong> Outputs are filtered for harmful, inaccurate, or sensitive content before display</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Which queries trigger AI Overviews?</h3>
        <p>AI Overviews appear for specific query patterns and are absent from others. Understanding this distinction determines where to invest optimization effort.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Queries that trigger vs skip AI Overviews</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Query type</th><th>AI Overview?</th><th>Example</th><th>SEO implication</th></tr>
            </thead>
