        <h2 id="examples">Real SGE optimization examples</h2>

        <h3>Informational content site — before and after citation strategy</h3>
        <p>A B2B software review site ranked #2 for "best project management software for agencies." After SGE rollout, their CTR dropped 41% — the AI Overview answered the query with a synthesized list before users needed to click. They restructured their article with: a direct 50-word answer at the top, a structured comparison table, numbered evaluation criteria, and FAQPage schema. Within 90 days, the article was cited in the AI Overview for that query. Traffic recovered to 85% of pre-SGE levels despite still ranking #2.</p>

        <h3>Local service business — unaffected by SGE</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company's primary keywords ("emergency plumber Austin," "pipe repair near me") do not trigger AI Overviews because they have local-with-map-intent. Their local pack rankings and Google Business Profile optimization remain the primary traffic drivers, unaffected by SGE. Local businesses with local-intent keywords are largely insulated from SGE's CTR impact.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">SGE vs featured snippets — which matters more?</h2>
        <p>Both provide above-the-fold answers. The mechanisms and optimization approaches differ.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Featured snippets</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Pulls content verbatim from a single ranking page</li>
              <li>The source page is prominently linked — drives significant CTR</li>
              <li>Won by ranking in top 5 and having well-structured content</li>
              <li>Established — understood optimization playbook</li>
              <li>One winner per query</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>AI Overviews (SGE)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Synthesizes from multiple pages — not verbatim</li>
              <li>Multiple sources cited — less traffic concentration per source</li>
              <li>Won by content quality, structure, and E-E-A-T signals</li>
              <li>Newer — optimization playbook still evolving</li>
              <li>Multiple winners (3–5 cited sources typically)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices to optimize for SGE / AI Overviews</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Answer the query in 40–60 words at the top of the page.</strong> AI systems extract the first clear, direct answer they encounter. A snippet-answer section immediately after the H1 is the highest-leverage structural change for citation optimization.</li>
          <li><strong>Use question-formatted H2 and H3 headings.</strong> "What is X?" "How does X work?" "When should you use X?" These match query patterns that trigger AI Overviews and help the LLM locate relevant sections within your content.</li>
          <li><strong>Include structured lists and comparison tables.</strong> AI systems extract tables for comparison queries. Ordered lists for how-to steps. Both formats are disproportionately cited relative to unstructured prose.</li>
          <li><strong>Add FAQPage schema markup with 4–6 questions.</strong> Google explicitly uses FAQPage answers in AI Overviews. Schema-marked FAQs are more likely to be extracted than identical content without markup.</li>
          <li><strong>Build topical authority across multiple related articles.</strong> AI systems prefer sources that demonstrate domain expertise, not just keyword optimization. A single article does not build citation authority; a cluster of 10–15 related articles does.</li>
          <li><strong>Demonstrate E-E-A-T explicitly.</strong> Author credentials, cited external sources, original data, and expert quotes all signal to AI systems that your content is authoritative. Include author bios, cite primary sources with links, and reference original research where available.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating SGE as a threat rather than a targeting shift</div>
          <p>Marketers who focus on the CTR drop number miss the strategic point: SGE is a channel redistribution, not channel elimination. The queries where you lose CTR are exactly the queries where you gain citation authority by restructuring content. The correct response is not to avoid informational content — it is to restructure existing informational content for citation.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common SGE optimization mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Writing long intros before answering the query</strong> — AI systems extract the first direct answer; burying it in 300 words of background means you are not cited</li>
          <li><strong>Prose-only content for comparison queries</strong> — tables are extracted significantly more often than prose for comparison queries</li>
          <li><strong>No FAQPage schema</strong> — schema-marked FAQs are disproportionately included in AI Overviews versus unstructured Q&amp;A sections</li>
          <li><strong>Single-article topical coverage</strong> — one authoritative article is less likely to be cited than a site with 10 interconnected articles on related topics</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring E-E-A-T signals</strong> — unnamed authors, no external citations, no original data — these gaps reduce citation probability</li>
          <li><strong>Optimizing for SGE on transactional or local queries</strong> — these query types rarely trigger AI Overviews; effort is better spent on intent-matched optimization</li>
        </ul>

